@RequestBeanScope = You want a new bean instance for every HTTP request.

So:
one user request → one bean object
next request → new bean object

Use case:
1. logged-in user info
2. request metadata
3. correlation ID
4. Multi-tenant request resolution
5. Request-specific caching

Suppose multiple service calls in same request need same expensive data.

Instead of hitting DB repeatedly:

@Component
@RequestScope
public class RequestCache {

    private Map<String, Object> cache = new HashMap<>();

    public Object get(String key) {
        return cache.get(key);
    }

    public void put(String key, Object value) {
        cache.put(key, value);
    }
}

Ques: What interceptors can be processed before reaching to controller layer ?
Ans: Filters = infrastructure-level. BEFORE DispatcherServlet and AFTER response returns
Interceptors = Works AFTER DispatcherServlet but BEFORE controller. Example role authorization, locale handling etc.

@Component
public class AuthInterceptor implements HandlerInterceptor {

    @Override
    public boolean preHandle(
            HttpServletRequest request,
            HttpServletResponse response,
            Object handler) {

        System.out.println("Before controller");

        return true;
    }
}

Register Intercepter:
@Configuration
public class WebConfig implements WebMvcConfigurer {

    @Autowired
    private AuthInterceptor interceptor;

    @Override
    public void addInterceptors(InterceptorRegistry registry) {
        registry.addInterceptor(interceptor);
    }
}
